    "synopsis": "[A] 1 Enoch 57 concludes the Second Parable with a vision of Israel's restoration from exile and the judgment of the nations who oppressed them. Enoch sees angels measuring out chains and instruments of judgment for 'the kings and the mighty' who have scattered God's chosen ones. [B] The chapter presents a theology of divine justice: the dispersal of Israel is temporary, but the punishment of the oppressors is eternal. [C] The imagery draws on prophetic restoration oracles (Isaiah 11:11-16, Jeremiah 31:7-14, Ezekiel 37:21-28) while adding apocalyptic intensity—the return is not merely political but cosmic, involving angelic agents and eschatological judgment. The 'holy and elect ones' are gathered from the four corners of the earth to witness the vindication of the Chosen One (Messiah). This chapter bridges Second Temple hope for national restoration with apocalyptic expectation of a transformed world order under divine rule.",
    
