    "ane_backdrop": "The vision of diaspora return and enemy judgment draws on ancient Near Eastern conquest narratives but inverts them. In Assyrian and Babylonian annals, kings boast of scattering conquered peoples 'to the four winds' and resettling lands with foreign populations (e.g., Sargon II's deportation policies, 2 Kings 17:24). The Cyrus Cylinder (539 BC) presents the Persian king as the restorer of displaced peoples and their gods—a propaganda piece that nonetheless reflects ANE expectations that legitimate rule includes reversing unjust exiles. 1 Enoch 57 radicalizes this: the return is not by human decree (even a benevolent Cyrus) but by angelic intervention. The 'measuring' of chains for judgment echoes Mesopotamian divine council scenes where gods determine fates, but here YHWH's angels execute judgment without debate or dissent. The Parthians and Medes represent the eastern powers that succeeded Babylon and Persia—historical enemies transformed into eschatological types of all anti-God nations.",
    
